Edwardian musical comedy was form British musical theatre that extended beyond the reign King Edward VII both direction beginning the early 1890s when the Gilbert and Sullivan operas dominance had ended until the rise the American musicals Jerome Kern Rodgers and Hart George Gershwin and Cole Porter following the First World War Between Town 1892 and The Maid the Mountains premiering 1917 this new style musical theatre became dominant the musical stage Britain and the rest the Englishspeaking world The popularity Town and Gaiety Girl 1893 led astonishing number hits over the next three decades the most successful which included The Shop Girl 1894 The Geisha 1896 Florodora 1899 Chinese Honeymoon 1901 The Earl and the Girl 1903 The Arcadians 1909 Our Miss Gibbs 1909 The Quaker Girl 1910 Betty 1914 Chu Chin Chow 1916 and The Maid the Mountains 1917 Edwardian musical comedy began the last decade the Victorian era and captured the optimism energy and good humour the new century and the Edwardian era well providing comfort during the First World War The Gaiety Theatres wellloved but racy burlesques were coming the end their popularity and was the run phenomenally successful familyfriendly Gilbert and Sullivan operas These two genres had dominated the musical stage since the 1870s few lighter more romantic comic operas beginning with Dorothy 1886 found success and showed that audiences wanted something lighter than operetta but more coherent construction than burlesque that featured the modern fashions and culture the day The father the Edwardian musical was George The Guvnor Edwardes took over the Gaiety Theatre the 1880s and first improved the quality the old Gaiety Theatre burlesques Perceiving that their time had passed experimented with moderndress familyfriendly musical theatre style with breezy popular songs snappy romantic banter and stylish spectacle These drew the traditions Savoy opera and also used elements burlesque and Americans Harrigan and Hart Their plots were simple and they included elaborate displays contemporary fashion and settings and lighthearted parody modern social convention and topical issues replaced the bawdy women burlesque with his respectable corps dancing singing Gaiety Girls who wore the latest fashions and also showed off their bodies chorus lines and bathing attire well singing complete the musical and visual fun These shows were immediately widely copied other London theatres and then America The first Edwardian musical comedy was Town 1892 Its success together with the even greater sensation Gaiety Girl 1893 confirmed Edwardes the path was taking These musical comedies called them revolutionized the London stage and set the tone for the next three decades According musical theatre writer Andrew Lamb The British Empire and America began fall for the appeal the Edwardian musical comedy from the time when Gaiety Girl was taken world tour 1894 Edwardes early Gaiety hits included series light romantic poor maiden loves aristocrat and wins him against all odds shows usually with the word Girl the title After Gaiety Girl came The Shop Girl 1894 The Circus Girl 1896 and Runaway Girl 1898 The heroines were independent young women who often earned their own livings The stories followed familiar plot line chorus girl breaks into high society shop girl makes good marriage There was always misunderstanding during act one and engagement the end the words contemporary review Edwardes musicals were Light bright and enjoyable Later Gaiety Theatre girl musicals included The Orchid 1903 The Spring Chicken 1905 The Girls Gottenberg 1907 Our Miss Gibbs 1909 The Sunshine Girl 1912 and The Girl the Film 1913 Perhaps balance the girl musicals the Gaiety also presented series what could described boy musicals such The Messenger Boy 1900 The Toreador 1901 The New Aladdin 1906 and Theodore and 1916 Edwardes expanded his empire other theatres and presented slightly more complex comedy hits beginning with Artists Model 1895 The Geisha 1896 and San Toy 1899 each ran for more than two years and found great international success capitalizing the British craze for all things oriental Other Edwardes hits included The Girl from Kays 1902 The Earl and the Girl 1903 and The Quaker Girl 1910 The chief glories Edwardian musical comedies lie their musical scores their best these combined the delicacy and sophistication operetta with the robust tunefulness the music hall The major composers the genre were Sidney Jones The Geisha Ivan Caryll Our Miss Gibbs Lionel Monckton The Quaker Girl Howard Talbot Chinese Honeymoon Leslie Stuart Florodora and Paul Rubens Miss Hook Holland Scores were constantly refreshed with additional specialty numbers and rearranged often several different composers and lyricists keep audiences coming back Important writers included Adrian Ross Harry Greenbank Percy Greenbank Owen Hall Charles Taylor and Oscar Asche Generally the book lyrics and music were each written different people which was first for the musical stage although now this the usual way doing things Adrian Ross wrote the lyrics for well over Edwardian musicals Besides Edwardes American producer Charles Frohman and actormanagers like Seymour Hicks Robert Evett and George Grossmith were responsible for many these shows The musicals were frequently built around resident company artists and the greatest stars the era included actresses Marie Tempest Gertie Millar Lily Elsie Ellaline Terriss and Phyllis Dare leading men such Hayden Coffin and Harry Grattan and comics such Rutland Barrington George Grossmith Huntley Wright and Edmund Payne One critic wrote Joseph Coyne that like other stars musical comedy good their pretending any one else see themselves and all ask that the authors and others shall give them every chance being themselves the most pronounced and personal fashion The Arcadians generally regarded the masterpiece the genre The composers were Monckton and Talbot both the height their powers The stor